"Laaksonen S., Pusenius J., Kumpula J., Venäläinen A., Kortet R., Oksanen A., Hoberg E.","Climate change promotes the emergence of serious disease outbreaks of filarioid nematodes",2010,"EcoHealth","7","1",,"7","13",,,10.1007/s10393-010-0308-z,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955301496&partnerID=40&md5=2b69f1732a31bbd85d8b7004ad42e5a9","Finnish Food Safety Authority Evira (FINPAR), P.O. Box 517, Oulu FI-90101, Finland; Finnish Game and Fisheries Research Institute, Joensuu FI-80100, Finland; Finnish Game and Fisheries Research Institute, Kaamanen FI-99910, Finland; Finnish Meteorological Institute, P.O. Box 503, Helsinki FI-00101, Finland; Department of Biology, University of Eastern Finland, P.O. Box 111, Joensuu FI-80101, Finland; US National Parasite Collection, ARS, USDA, Animal Parasitic Diseases Laboratory, BARC East 1180, 10300 Baltimore Avenue, Beltsville, MD 20705, United States","Laaksonen, S., Finnish Food Safety Authority Evira (FINPAR), P.O. Box 517, Oulu FI-90101, Finland; Pusenius, J., Finnish Game and Fisheries Research Institute, Joensuu FI-80100, Finland; Kumpula, J., Finnish Game and Fisheries Research Institute, Kaamanen FI-99910, Finland; Venäläinen, A., Finnish Meteorological Institute, P.O. Box 503, Helsinki FI-00101, Finland; Kortet, R., Department of Biology, University of Eastern Finland, P.O. Box 111, Joensuu FI-80101, Finland; Oksanen, A., Finnish Food Safety Authority Evira (FINPAR), P.O. Box 517, Oulu FI-90101, Finland; Hoberg, E., US National Parasite Collection, ARS, USDA, Animal Parasitic Diseases Laboratory, BARC East 1180, 10300 Baltimore Avenue, Beltsville, MD 20705, United States","Filarioid parasites represent major health hazards with important medical, veterinary, and economic implications, and considerable potential to affect the everyday lives of tens of millions of people globally (World Health Organization, 2007). Scenarios for climate change vary latitudinally and regionally and involve direct and indirect linkages for increasing temperature and the dissemination, amplification, and invasiveness of vector-borne parasites. High latitude regions are especially influenced by global climate change and thus may be prone to altered associations and dynamics for complex host-pathogen assemblages and emergence of disease with cascading effects on ecosystem structure. Although the potential for substantial ecological perturbation has been identified, few empirical observations have emanated from systems across the Holarctic. Coincidental with decades of warming, and anomalies of high temperature and humidity in the sub-Arctic region of Fennoscandia, the mosquito-borne filarioid nematode Setaria tundra is now associated with emerging epidemic disease resulting in substantial morbidity and mortality for reindeer and moose. We describe a host-parasite system that involves reindeer, arthropods, and nematodes, which may contribute as a factor to ongoing declines documented for this ungulate species across northern ecosystems. We demonstrate that mean summer temperatures exceeding 14°C drive the emergence of disease due to S. tundra. An association between climate and emergence of filarioid parasites is a challenge to ecosystem services with direct effects on public health, sustainability of free-ranging and domestic ungulates, and ultimately food security for subsistence cultures at high latitudes. © 2010 The Author(s).","emerging diseases; filarioid nematodes; global warming; reindeer populations; sub-Arctic; vector-borne diseases","animal; animal disease; Arctic; article; climate change; communicable disease; disease carrier; disease transmission; ecosystem; epidemic; growth, development and aging; host parasite interaction; nematode; nematodiasis; parasitology; physiology; reindeer; temperature; Animals; Arctic Regions; Climate Change; Communicable Diseases, Emerging; Disease Outbreaks; Disease Vectors; Ecosystem; Host-Parasite Interactions; Nematoda; Nematode Infections; 